definition.value: A member of the class of  phenols that is phenol substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 4.
An aminopyrimidine in which a pyrimidine core carries amino substituents at positions 2, 4 and 6.
An imine that is L-tyrosine bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at position 2 as well as a (2-phenylethylidene)amino substituent at position 5.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid that comprises of a propyl substituent on a pentanoic acid stem.
A member of the class of  alkylamines that is propane substituted by an amino group at C-1.
A 3'-deoxyribonucleoside having guanine as the nucleobase.
A catechol bearing an additional fluoro substituent at position 3.
The ester obtained by formal condensation of mandelic acid and 3,3,5-tricyclohexanol. It is a direct-acting smooth muscle relaxant used to dilate blood vessels.

A tripeptide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-[(5-methyl-1,2-oxazol-3-yl)carbonyl]-L-alanyl-L-valine with the amino group of benzyl (2E,4S)-4-(L-leucylamino)-5-[(3S)-2-oxopyrrolidin-3-yl]pent-2-enoate. It is an inhibitor of the main protease of SARS-CoV-2.

A  primary arylamine that is aniline in which the hydrogens at the 3- and 4-positions are replaced by methyl groups. A low-melting, crystalline solid, it is used in the production of vitamin B2, dyes, pesticides and other chemicals.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydroxy groups are located at positions 3 and 5.
A substituted diphenylfuran in which two amino[(1-methylbutyl)amino]methyl substituents are located at the two para-positions on the phenyl rings.
A methylpyridine that is pyridine substituted by a methyl group at position 3.
An apo carotenoid triterpenoid compound consisting of 8'-apo-beta-carotene having a hydroxy group at the 8'-position and an (R)-hydroxy substituent at the 3-position.
A mononitrotoluene carrying a nitro group at position 3.
An oct-1-en-3-ol that has R-configuration.
An optically active form of 1,2-distearoylphosphatidylethanolamine zwitterion that has (R)-configuration.
An N-alkylpiperazine in which one nitrogen of the piperazine ring is substituted by a methyl group, while the other is substituted by a diphenylmethyl group.
A benzene which is substituted by a 3-oxopropyl group at position 1.
An N-acylpyrrolidine that is the pyrrolidine amide of (2S,3S)-2-amino-3-{3-[4-(methylsulfonyl)phenyl]-1,2,4-oxadiazol-5-yl}butanoic acid.
A triazolopyrazine that is a rigid cyclohexylamine analogue of sitagliptin.
